{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/working-with-the-census-api-7ed105448f13", "time": 1683010385.217189, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/working-with-the-census-api-7ed105448f13/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Working with the Census API. Collecting data to study public health\u2026 | by Nick Doiron | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Working with the Census API", "description": "I\u2019m a software developer at Tufts University, and my main project is a district-drawing website Districtr.org, which covers all forms of school, city, county, and legislative districts. We check that\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://districtr.org", "anchor_text": "Districtr.org", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://popfactfinder.planning.nyc.gov/", "anchor_text": "popfactfinder.planning.nyc.gov", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://www.qgis.org/en/site/", "anchor_text": "qgis.org", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://www.census.gov/cgi-bin/geo/shapefiles/index.php", "anchor_text": "census.gov/cgi-bin/geo/shapefiles/index.php", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://www.dataschool.io/cloud-services-for-jupyter-notebook/", "anchor_text": "a free notebook", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://github.com/mapmeld/use-this-now/blob/main/README.md#census-api", "anchor_text": "github.com/mapmeld/use-this-now/blob/main/README.md#census-api", "paragraph_index": 19}], "all_paragraphs": ["I\u2019m a software developer at Tufts University, and my main project is a district-drawing website Districtr.org, which covers all forms of school, city, county, and legislative districts. We check that districts have equal population (and allow users to evaluate their plans) through careful use of Census data.", "You may be aware of the current Census (please fill it out!) but if you\u2019re a data scientist or political activist, you should know where to find previous Census records for your present-day projects.", "This March, my colleagues started using our Census work to map where demographics especially at-risk for coronavirus live \u2014 specifically the elderly, group housing, and households that don\u2019t speak English. Knowing the concentration of these populations, versus hospital capacity, would guide our research and advice to policy makers.", "Researchers are also comparing other datasets on policing \u2014 911 calls, traffic stops, arrests, police violence, sentencing\u2014 to local populations via Census data. For example, we can look at imprisonment at a national level vs. race and ethnicity data:", "In June, John Keefe made a series of how-to posts about collecting race and ethnicity data from the 2010 Census to police precincts of multiple cities:", "This was an interesting project, but I wanted to make two points:", "If you want to be a Census data scientist, you should be comfortable both with the decennial Census, and the American Community Survey (ACS). As of this writing, one of our best and most recent sources was the 2014\u20132018 5-year ACS.", "Why don\u2019t we use the more recent ACS for everything?The decennial Census publishes population counts for every \u2018Census block\u2019. The ACS has more recent and more detailed statistics, but we have to zoom out one level to the \u2018block group\u2019. For other data points (such as language and national ancestry) we must zoom out again to the \u2018tract\u2019 level.", "The size of each \u2018Census block\u2019 or tract is not consistent when you look at urban or rural or coastal areas. Some blocks cover unpopulated parks, rivers, and airports; some are city blocks or prisons.", "Explore blocks and tract maps on NYC\u2019s popfactfinder.planning.nyc.gov", "You can view map data in GIS software. The leading free/open source application is called QGIS: qgis.org", "You can download 2010 blocks or 2018 block groups as shapefiles fromcensus.gov/cgi-bin/geo/shapefiles/index.php", "Now that you have the shapes, let\u2019s collect several columns of data from the Census API.If you can\u2019t install Python and pip, or access the Census website because of your computer or internet settings, you can likely get a free notebook on Google CoLab, or NextJournal.", "If you\u2019d like to have some of the API code worked out in advance, try this Python package from DataMade:", "There\u2019s probably an R package, too. Leave a comment with your favorite.", "This is how I find the columns that I want and download them from the Census API. Your approach can vary from this.", "If you were using the 2010 Census, what would you change?", "There are two major approaches that I know of:", "Blocks fit inside of block groups which fit inside of tracts, so we can sum them up and calculate populations precisely. If we draw other shapes on the map, such as a walking distance around subway stations, the fit is no longer perfect; we can only estimate the population inside.", "This article is from July 2020. For any new recommendations see my GitHub README github.com/mapmeld/use-this-now/blob/main/README.md#census-api", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7ed105448f13&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fworking-with-the-census-api-7ed105448f13&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fworking-with-the-census-api-7ed105448f13&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layou